                <notesStmt>
                    <annot type="links" xml:id="annot_ab6d94b3">
                        <ptr label="Digital online edition" mimetype="" target="www.kb.dk/dcm/kaleidakustikon/" xml:id="ptr_07b5a61a"/>
                    </annot>
                    <annot type="general_description" xml:id="annot_ce44c529">Friedrich Kuhlau's (1786-1832) <rend fontstyle="italic">Kaleidakustikon</rend>
                    is part of a tradition of musical games which enjoyed some popularity, 
                    especially during the second half of the eighteenth century. 
                    The games have in common that they contain a series of musical fragments 
                    which may be combined into small compositions according to certain rules. 
                    It is left to the players of the game to select, more or less randomly, 
                    a combination by throwing dice, for example.<lb/>
                        <rend fontstyle="italic">Kaleidakustikon</rend> consists of 21 piles of cards; each of the piles (labeled A to V) contains eleven cards numbered 2 to 12 (namely, all the scores possible when throwing two 
dices). With one card selected from each pile, the cards form a tripartite waltz, 24 bars in length, to be played in a rondo-like form.</annot>
                </notesStmt>
